Introduction

In this Rmd file, the Weighted Directed Random Walk will be performed on the RPTEC dataset.This involves performing a random walk over the network, where nodes present genes and edges present the directions of the network. The procedures described by (Hui et al, 2024) and (Liu et al, 2013) are followed as much as possible. However, they used predefined pathways and this project used co-expressed modules. So, some things will differ and it will be mentioned where it differs.

First, the directions of the network will be constructed based on the median(TOM) values of genes in a module, if media(TOM(gene A)) > median(TOM(gene B)) than A has an edge to B: A->B (represented as 1). This direction will be weighted by the Topological Overlap Matrix (TOM). The original article uses predefined pathways for this. Then, the directions will be reversed, because “a web page is important if other pages point to it” and therefore also genes (Liu et al, 2013). Also,an artificial ground node will be used, which is bidirectionally connected to every gene that has no connections to other genes and one directionally connected to every other gene. This is done to make sure that every node is connected and there are no 0-out of degree connections (Liu et al, 2013), making sure that the progation goes well and the walker converges. This results in the Weighted Graph \(G\).

After that, the random walker will be performed:

\[ W_{t+1} = (1 - r) A_{M_j} \cdot W_t + r W_0 \] Here, the \(r\) represents the restart probability, set at 0.7 (Hui et al). This represents the chance to return to the initial weight vector (\(W_0\)), which represents the initial differential signal for each gene, based on biological and statistical significance: -log10(padj) * abs(Log2FC). The original article used t-values, but the degrees of freedom are not known. So this score is proposed.

\[ W_0(g_i) = -\log_{10} \left( p_{\mathrm{adj}}(g_i) \right) \cdot \left| \log_2 \mathrm{FC}(g_i) \right| \]

The \(A_{Mj}\) represents the row normalized adjacency matrix of the Graph \(G\). The \(W_t\) vector represents the weight of the nodes (genes) at time \(t\) and the \(W_{t+1}\) vector represents the weight of the nodes (genes) at time \(t+1\).

The recursive walker will be performed until the L1-norm ,the difference (delta), between \(W_t\) and \(W_{t+1}\) converges to \(10^{–10}\) and this limit, the \(W_{∞}\), will be obtained for each gene. The \(W_{∞}\) of the ground node will be evenly distributed over the other genes in the module.

Afterwards, the module activty for module \(M_j\) will be calculated using the following formula, only using genes that have a padj < 0.05 and an absolute log2fc greater than 1.0:

\[ wDRW(M_j) = \frac{ \sum_{i=1}^{n_j} W_\infty(g_i) \cdot \log_2 \mathrm{FC}(g_i) } { \sqrt{n_j} \cdot \sqrt{ \sum_{i=1}^{n_j} \left( W_\infty(g_i) \right)^2 } } \]

Here, the \(W_{∞}\) represents the weight of each gene in the network and log2fc represents the (signed) expression value. The sum of all the \(W_{∞}\) vector multiplied by the abs log2fc of the genes will be divided by the square root of the sum of the squared \(W_{∞}\) vector for each gene. The result is a wDRW score that represents the activity value of a modelling, integrating both differential expression and network importance of genes.

Calculating W0 for the Directed Random Walker

The initial artical uses t-scores (Hui et al, 2024) for constructing the initial weight (W_0) of the walker, however the degrees of freedom are not known. So therefore, a different score will be used. For this the “walker score” will be used, which is proposed as the abs(Log2FC) * -log10(padj). To account for statistical significance and biological significance.

expression_long_filtered$walker_score <- abs(expression_long_filtered$log2fc) *
                                         (-log10(expression_long_filtered$padj))

Constructing the Directed Graph

To construct the Directed Graph for use in the Directed Random Walk. The median (TOM) scores will be used for genes in the same module. If median(TOM(gene A)) > median(TOM(gene B)) than A has an edge to B: A->B. Then the directions will be reversed: a webpage is important if other webpages point to it (Hui et al, 2024). This directed Graph will then be weighted by the TOM. Resulting in a weighted Directed Graph.

Correlation EGs

No correlation EGs are given for the RPTEC dataset, so these will be calculated first. this is not used anymore, but was before, so the chunks are still included

expression_cor_eg <- expression_joined %>%
  # Remove module 0, because this is removed in the GRR_vs_eg_score df
  filter(module_number != 0) %>%
  
  # Add eg_score per sample_id + module_number in expression df
  left_join(GRR_vs_eg_score, by = c("sample_id", "module_number")) %>%
  
  # calculate cor_eg per sample_id and module for every gene
  group_by(entrez_id, module_number) %>%
  mutate(
    cor_eg = abs(cor(log2fc, eg_score, method = "pearson", use = "pairwise.complete.obs"))
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  
  # Keep only relevant columns
  select(entrez_id, sample_id, module_number, log2fc, eg_score, cor_eg)

Calculating the Directed Graph

The directed graph will be calculated in the walker loop for each module+condition.

Perform the walker on one module to learn how it works practically

Before performing the walker on the whole RPTEC dataset, it will be tested on one module to assess how it works exactly. Module 100 was selected with condition LU_HRPTECTERT1_SINGLE_CITRININ_T3_C3 (random), because this module is small (5 genes) and therefore easy to visualize the weights of the individual genes

Defining the Directed Graph

Again, if median(TOM(A)) > median(TOM(B)) then edge: A -> B. However, these edges will be reverted: a gene is important if other genes point to it (Liu et al, 2013)

TOM_medians <- apply(TOM_sub, 1, median, na.rm = TRUE)

# Directional Graph based on TOM median
D <- outer(TOM_medians, TOM_medians, FUN = function(x, y) as.numeric(x < y))
rownames(D) <- colnames(D) <- names(TOM_medians)

W_directed <- D * TOM_sub # Weight the directions with the TOM

Adding a ground node

A ground node will be added to ensure that the walker does not get stuck on a gene without outgoing edges. (Liu et al, 2013)

genes <- rownames(W_directed)
ground_node <- "GROUND"
n <- length(genes)

# Maak empty matrix
W_plus <- matrix(0, nrow = n + 1, ncol = n + 1)
rownames(W_plus) <- colnames(W_plus) <- c(genes, ground_node)

# Add original matrix
W_plus[genes, genes] <- W_directed

# Add ground node to genes without outgoing edges
zero_rows <- which(rowSums(W_directed) == 0)
if (length(zero_rows) > 0) {
  W_plus[genes[zero_rows], ground_node] <- 1e-4  # This will be normalized to "1" later
  
  # Ground node has equal weight to every other gene in the module
  W_plus[ground_node, genes] <- 1
}

# Normalization of the matrix
diag(W_plus) <- 0
A <- W_plus / rowSums(W_plus)

Defining the initial probability, based on the ‘walker score’

The initial probability will be assigned on the earlier calculated walker score.

# Prepare the initial walker probability (W0) based on the proposed walker score. 
  # Initialize W0 with all genes 0
  W0 <- rep(0, length(rownames(A)))
  names(W0) <- rownames(A)
  
  # Select only the walker score for significant genes
  W0_sig <- expr_sub %>%
    filter(entrez_id %in% rownames(A)) %>% # , padj < 0.05 was left out to reduce over estimation
    select(entrez_id, walker_score) %>%
    tibble::deframe()
  
  # Fill W0 only for significant genes
  W0[names(W0_sig)] <- abs(W0_sig)
  
  # Normalization
  W0 <- W0 / sum(W0)
  
  # Security: make sure the genes match
  stopifnot(all(names(W0) == rownames(A)))
print(W0)

Running the walker

# Run random walk with restart

r <- 0.7
W_prev <- W0
convergence <- data.frame(iteration = 0, delta = NA)
W_all <- list(W_prev)

for (i in 1:1000) { 
  W_new <- (1 - r) * A %*% W_prev + r * W0
  delta <- sum(abs(W_new - W_prev))
  convergence <- rbind(convergence, data.frame(iteration = i, delta = delta))
  W_all[[i + 1]] <- W_new
  if (delta < 1e-10) break
  W_prev <- W_new
}

W_inf <- as.numeric(W_new)
names(W_inf) <- rownames(A)
print(summary(W_inf))

The walker output will be visualized to understand it better

Visualization of the convergence

First the L1-norm, the difference between \(W_t\) and \(W_{t+1}\), will be visualized to assess how the walker converges.

# Visualize convergence

ggplot(convergence[-1, ], aes(x = iteration, y = delta)) +

  theme_minimal()

As shown above, the L1-norm decreases after iterations, making the recursive walker converge to the base case (L1-norm 10^-10).

Perform the walker on the whole RPTEC dataset

The above applied logic was now incorporated in a function to loop over the whole dataset and calculate DRW scores.

Function

This function will be called for every combination of module and condition in a loop. It follows the same procedure as the above calculation done “by hand”.

compute_drw_score <- function(condition_id, module_nr, expression_df, TOM) {
  # Subset the expression dataframe for the specified module and sample
  expr_sub <- expression_df %>%
    filter(sample_id == condition_id, module_number == module_nr)

  if (nrow(expr_sub) == 0) {
    return(tibble(condition_id = condition_id, module_nr = module_nr, drw_score = 0))
  } # To ensure not crashing the function

  # Extract correlation vector
  cor_vec <- expr_sub$cor_eg
  names(cor_vec) <- expr_sub$entrez_id

  # Intersect genes with TOM matrix and create a subset
  genes_in_TOM <- intersect(expr_sub$entrez_id, rownames(TOM))
  cor_vec <- cor_vec[genes_in_TOM]
  TOM_sub <- TOM[genes_in_TOM, genes_in_TOM, drop = FALSE]

  if (length(genes_in_TOM) < 2) {
    return(tibble(condition_id = condition_id, module_nr = module_nr, drw_score = 0))
  } # To ensure not crashing the function

  # Create directed edges: gene B -> gene A if Median TOM(A) > median TOM(B) as explained above
  TOM_medians <- apply(TOM_sub, 1, median, na.rm = TRUE)

  # Directional Graph
  D <- outer(TOM_medians, TOM_medians, FUN = function(x, y) as.numeric(x < y))
  rownames(D) <- colnames(D) <- names(TOM_medians)

  # Weight the directed edges by the TOM
  W_directed <- D * TOM_sub

  # Add ground node to avoid 0 out of degree nodes
  genes <- rownames(W_directed)
  ground_node <- "GROUND"
  n <- length(genes)

  W_plus <- matrix(0, nrow = n + 1, ncol = n + 1)
  rownames(W_plus) <- colnames(W_plus) <- c(genes, ground_node)

  # Add original weighted adjacency to W_plus
  W_plus[genes, genes] <- W_directed

  # Add edges from ground node and to it if a row has no outgoing edges
  zero_rows <- which(rowSums(W_directed) == 0)
  if (length(zero_rows) > 0) {
    W_plus[genes[zero_rows], ground_node] <- 1e-4 # This will be normalized to 1 later
    W_plus[ground_node, genes] <- 1
  }

  # Normalize the matrix row-wise
  diag(W_plus) <- 0
  row_sums <- rowSums(W_plus)
  row_sums[row_sums == 0] <- 1e-10  # prevent division by zero (not possible if all goes well)
  A <- W_plus / row_sums

  # Prepare the initial walker probability (W0) based on the proposed walker score. To 'boost' the significant genes, they only get an innitial weight (W0), this is done to        reduce low DRW scores with high wGRR as this was shown in subset calculations
 
  # Initialize W0 with all genes 0
  W0 <- rep(0, length(rownames(A)))
  names(W0) <- rownames(A)
  
  # Select only the walker score for significant genes
  W0_sig <- expr_sub %>%
    filter(entrez_id %in% rownames(A)) %>% #, padj < 0.05 
    select(entrez_id, walker_score) %>%
    tibble::deframe()
  
  # Fill W0 only for significant genes
  W0[names(W0_sig)] <- abs(W0_sig)
  
  # Security: no zeros
  if (sum(W0) == 0 || any(is.na(W0))) {
    return(tibble(condition_id = condition_id, module_nr = module_nr, drw_score = 0))
  }
  
  # Normalization
  W0 <- W0 / sum(W0)
  
  # Security: make sure the genes match
  stopifnot(all(names(W0) == rownames(A)))

  # Run random walk with restart
  r <- 0.7
  W_prev <- W0
  for (i in 1:1000) {
    W_new <- (1 - r) * A %*% W_prev + r * W0
    delta <- sum(abs(W_new - W_prev))
    if (is.na(delta)) return(NULL)
    if (delta < 1e-10) break
    W_prev <- W_new
  }

  W_inf <- as.numeric(W_new)
  names(W_inf) <- rownames(A)

  # Evenly redistribute W_inf of the ground to the other nodes
  if ("GROUND" %in% names(W_inf)) {
    ground_mass <- W_inf["GROUND"]
    W_inf <- W_inf[names(W_inf) != "GROUND"]
    W_inf <- W_inf + ground_mass / length(W_inf)
  }

  # Compute pathway activity using only genes with padj < 0.05
  activity_df <- expression_df %>%
    filter(sample_id == condition_id,
           module_number == module_nr,
           entrez_id %in% names(W_inf),
           padj < 0.05,
           abs(log2fc) > 1.0) %>%
    select(entrez_id, log2fc) %>%
    mutate(W_inf = W_inf[entrez_id],
           term = W_inf * log2fc)

  numerator <- sum(activity_df$term, na.rm = TRUE)
  denominator <- sqrt(sum(activity_df$W_inf^2, na.rm = TRUE))
  pathway_activity_score <- ifelse(denominator == 0, 0, numerator / denominator)

  tibble(condition_id = condition_id, module_nr = module_nr, drw_score = pathway_activity_score)
}

Evaluate the DRW scores on the RPTEC with the GRR and wGRR metric

The DRW scores will be evaluated on the Gene Response Rate and Weighted Gene Response Rate (wGRR) metric, which is proposed as an evaluation metric for the topological activation of every unique combination of condition and module. The GRR and wGRR are presented as the following formulas:

\[ \mathrm{GRR}(M_j) = \frac{ \displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^{n_j} \left( |\log_2 \mathrm{FC}_i| > 1.0 \,\wedge\, p_{\mathrm{adj},i} < 0.05 \right)} { n_j } \]

\[ \mathrm{wGRR}(M_j) = \frac{ \displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^{n_j} \left( |\log_2 \mathrm{FC}_i| > 1.0 \,\wedge\, p_{\mathrm{adj},i} < 0.05 \right) \cdot \mathrm{median(TOM)}_i }{ \sum_{i=1}^{n_j} \mathrm{median(TOM)}_i } \] The GRR represents the proportion of significantly expressed genes in a module (abs log2fc > 1.0 and padj < 0.05) and the wGRR weighs this proportion by the median(TOM) of a gene within a module.

Median TOM

get_module_relative_tom <- function(TOM, gene_module_df) {
  gene_module_df <- gene_module_df %>%
    distinct(entrez_id, module_number) %>%
    filter(entrez_id %in% rownames(TOM))

  gene_module_df %>%
    group_by(module_number) %>%
    group_modify(~ {
      genes <- .x$entrez_id
      sub_tom <- TOM[genes, genes, drop = FALSE]
      diag(sub_tom) <- NA

      tom_median <- matrixStats::rowMedians(sub_tom, na.rm = TRUE)
      total_median <- sum(tom_median, na.rm = TRUE)
      tom_relative <- tom_median / total_median

      tibble(
        entrez_id = genes,
        tom_median = tom_median,
        tom_relative = tom_relative
      )
    }) %>%
    ungroup()
}
# Calculate TOM weights
tom_weights <- get_module_relative_tom(TOM, expression_cor_eg)
# Join with expression
expression_cor_eg <- expression_cor_eg %>%
  left_join(tom_weights, by = c("entrez_id", "module_number")) %>%
  mutate(tom_median = as.numeric(tom_median), tom_relative = as.numeric(tom_relative))

Binomial Generalized Linear Model (GLM): GRR vs DRW

glm_data <- GRR_vs_DRW %>%
  filter(!is.na(GRR), !is.na(drw_zscore)) # This filtering was performed as the function was first tested on a subset, but the filtering is irrelevant for the whole dataset as there are no NAs
glm_fit <- glm(
  abs(GRR) ~ abs(drw_zscore), # absolute because of binomial
  data = glm_data,
  family = quasibinomial(link = "logit") # quasibinomial as the wGRR is a proportion multiplied by a continuous variable, the median(TOM)
)
# Make predictions and residuals

glm_dev_resid <- residuals(glm_fit, type = "deviance")

significant outliers

For each module and sample, we compare the observed number of significant genes to the expected number based on the binomial GLM, and calculate a two-sided z-score and p-value using the binomial standard error. By doing this, the significant outlying modules from the glm fit are identified.

GRR_glm_fit_df <- GRR_glm_fit_df %>%
  mutate(
    se_fit = sqrt(fitted_GRR * (1 - fitted_GRR) / module_size),
    z_score = GRR_resid / se_fit,
    p_value = 2 * pnorm(-abs(z_score))  # two-sided test
  )
GRR_glm_fit_df <- GRR_glm_fit_df %>%
  mutate(
    outlier = p_value < 0.05,
    outlier_direction = case_when(
      outlier & z_score > 0 ~ "Above fit",
      outlier & z_score < 0 ~ "Below fit",
      TRUE ~ "Not significant"
    )
  )
GRR_glm_fit_df <- GRR_glm_fit_df %>%
  mutate(module = paste0("hRPTECTERT1_", module_number)) %>%

significant outliers

For each module and sample, we compare the observed number of significant genes to the expected number based on the binomial GLM, and calculate a two-sided z-score and p-value using the binomial standard error. By doing this, the significant outlying modules from the glm fit are identified.

GRR_glm_fit_df <- GRR_glm_fit_df %>%
  mutate(
    se_fit = sqrt(fitted_wGRR * (1 - fitted_wGRR) / module_size),
    z_score = wGRR_resid / se_fit,
    p_value = 2 * pnorm(-abs(z_score))  # two-sided test
  )
GRR_glm_fit_df <- GRR_glm_fit_df %>%
  mutate(
    outlier = p_value < 0.05,
    outlier_direction = case_when(
      outlier & z_score > 0 ~ "Above fit",
      outlier & z_score < 0 ~ "Below fit",
      TRUE ~ "Not significant"
    )
  )
GRR_glm_fit_df <- GRR_glm_fit_df %>%
  filter(!is.na(module_number)) %>%
  mutate(module = paste0("hRPTECTERT1_", module_number)) %>%
  left_join(module_annotation, by = "module")
sum(GRR_glm_fit_df$outlier, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 6998

There are 6998 outliers found. This is less than the eg score.

outlier_density <- GRR_glm_fit_df %>%
  filter(outlier, module_number != 0) %>%
  group_by(outlier_direction) %>%
  summarise(
    total_outliers = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  bind_rows(
    tibble(
      outlier_direction = "Total",
      total_outliers = sum(.$total_outliers)
    )
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    total_modules = total_modules_all,
    total_conditions = total_conditions_all,
    density = total_outliers / (total_modules * total_conditions)
  )

Conclusion

The DRW shows less outliers and a more ‘robust’ fit than the EG score on both the GRR and wGRR metric in RPTEC. It will be further assessed using other evaluations if the wDRW is better on other metrics as well.
